    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-10-04T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-10-04T05:00:00-05:00" n="547"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d547">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">765.84/1554: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-10-04T11:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 4, 1935—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 4—10:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>415. Consulate’s 408, October 2, 5 p.m. A further communiqué has just been issued
                    by Secretariat giving the text of another telegram dated October 3 from
                        Suvich<note n="86" xml:id="d547fn86">Fulvio Suvich, Italian Under Secretary
                        of State for Foreign Affairs.</note> to the Secretary General. The text read
                    as follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“I have the honor to refer to the telegram from the Ethiopian Government
                            received on the 2nd instant by the League Secretariat. According to this
                            telegram Italian detachments have crossed the frontier south of Mount
                            Mussa Alli in the Sultanate of Aussa. In this connection the Italian
                            Government has the honor to state that apart from the fact that in the
                            region in question the frontier between Eritrea and the Sultanate of
                            Aussa has not yet been delimited, no military movement of Italian
                            detachments has taken place in that region. The report in question is
                            thus entirely unfounded.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
